<div class="comments-body">
<p>John,<br />
How are you?  A Fortune magazine article reports:<br />
"[Microsoft] product development groups shower [Bill Gates] with meticulously researched 'opportunity maps' showing the competitive landscape for a certain software market."<br />
These maps, of course, are foundational to Microsoft's efforts to come up with a package of services that are truly compelling and which would convince subscribers to sign up (the increase-lower-limit-of-expectations scenario).<br />
What does a company look like that is optimized to develop opportunity maps?<br />
As it happens, not long ago my business plan for an such a company was circulated internally at Microsoft.  I subsequently received the following e-mail from Randy Hinrichs, Manager of Microsoft Research's Learning Sciences<br />
and Technology Group:<br />
"Frank, you are a good man. Have you thought about joining this team? Your only alternative, of course, is venture capital. But their usual models require getting rid of the 'originator' within the first eighteen months. With Netscape it took a little longer, but you get the idea."<br />
The business plan is online, at www.opportunityservices.com/businessplan.html.<br />
Also, the Microsoft-specific lead-in can be seen at www.opportunityservices.com/indexms.html<br />
Let me know if you have any questions, comments, etc.<br />
